# Bug Detection Techniques

Pragmatic recipes for finding defects. The main agent file maps tiers to sections here. Run the commands, read the output, decide if there's an actionable finding. Do not skim.

> **Note:** All `rg` commands assume ripgrep is on PATH (it is in this repo's dev environment). Replace with equivalent `grep -rn` only if rg is unavailable.

---

## §1 — CRASH CLASS (P0)

Goal: surface every panic, uncaught throw, nil-deref, race that the codebase admits to.

### Go scans

```bash
# 1. Run the full test suite, capture failures verbatim
go test ./... -count=1 2>&1 | tee /tmp/bughunt-go-tests.log

# 2. Run with race detector on the changed packages (read git diff first to scope)
go test -race ./pkgs/tasks/... -count=1 2>&1 | tee /tmp/bughunt-race.log

# 3. Find every explicit panic on a request path
rg -n "\bpanic\(" pkgs/ internal/ cmd/ --type go

# 4. Find silenced linter / static-analysis findings
rg -n "//\s*nolint|//\s*lint:ignore" pkgs/ internal/ cmd/ --type go

# 5. Find type assertions WITHOUT comma-ok (will panic on wrong type)
#    Pattern: x.(T) on a line by itself or on RHS without ", ok"
rg -n "\.\([A-Z][A-Za-z0-9_]*\)" pkgs/ internal/ cmd/ --type go | rg -v ", ok"

# 6. Find unchecked map/slice indexing in hot paths
rg -n "\[[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z0-9_]*\]" pkgs/tasks/handler/ --type go | rg -v "_, ok :="

# 7. Vet pass
go vet ./...
```

**What to look for:**
- Any FAIL line in test output → P0 candidate
- DATA RACE in race output → P0 (concurrency, but presents as crash class)
- Panic in non-test code without an explicit boundary recovery → P0
- Nolint without a comment explaining why → suspicious, look at the underlying issue

### Web scans

```bash
# 1. Run the full Vitest suite
cd web && npm test -- --run 2>&1 | tee /tmp/bughunt-web-tests.log

# 2. Find every unguarded throw
rg -n "throw\s+(new\s+)?Error" web/src/ --type ts --type tsx

# 3. Find type-system escape hatches (these hide runtime crashes)
rg -n "\bas\s+any\b|\bas\s+unknown\s+as\b|@ts-ignore|@ts-expect-error" web/src/

# 4. Find promise chains without .catch
rg -n "\.then\(" web/src/ --type ts --type tsx -A 1 | rg -v "\.catch\("

# 5. Find async functions whose callers don't await or .catch
#    (manual review of recent diff is more reliable than grep here)
```

**What to look for:**
- Vitest failures → P0
- `as any` or `@ts-ignore` without an inline justifying comment → suspicious
- A `throw` inside a render function or a synchronous reducer → P0 (will crash React tree)

