## §2 — STATE / INVARIANT (P1)

Goal: find paths where state can end up wrong without anyone noticing.

### Go scans

```bash
# 1. Find write methods NOT inside a transaction wrapper
rg -n "db\.(Create|Save|Updates|Delete|Exec)" pkgs/tasks/store/ --type go -B 5 | rg -v "Transaction\("

# 2. Find dual-write candidates: cycle/phase mutation that doesn't co-write task_events
rg -ln "task_cycles|task_cycle_phases" pkgs/tasks/store/ --type go
# For each file, manually check that mutations also touch task_events in same tx

# 3. Find direct status mutations bypassing transitions
rg -n "\.Status\s*=" pkgs/tasks/ --type go | rg -v "_test.go"

# 4. Find admissions of broken invariants
rg -n "//\s*(TODO|FIXME|XXX|HACK).*invariant|//\s*(TODO|FIXME).*race|//\s*(TODO|FIXME).*broken" pkgs/ internal/ --type go
```

### Web scans

```bash
# 1. Find optimistic updates without rollback
rg -n "setQueryData|onMutate" web/src/ --type ts --type tsx -A 10 | rg -B 1 "onError" 

# 2. Find stale-closure setState patterns
rg -n "set[A-Z][a-zA-Z]*\(.*[+\-*/].*\)" web/src/ --type tsx
# (true positive: setX(x + 1); should be setX(prev => prev + 1))

# 3. Find mutations that don't invalidate related queries
rg -n "useMutation" web/src/ --type tsx -A 15 | rg -B 1 "invalidateQueries|setQueryData"
```

**What to look for:**
- Any store write outside a `db.Transaction(...)` block where multiple rows are affected
- `task_cycles` / `task_cycle_phases` writes without a co-located `task_events` insert
- Optimistic mutations with no `onError` rollback path
- `setX(x + 1)` patterns instead of `setX(prev => prev + 1)`

